Capital Rules for Trading
   Securities Seems Nearer
Capital standards for securities trading are being sought
as a means of protecting financial markets from the possible
collapse of securities firms.
   The teams meeting to discuss the issue didn't provide any
details concerning specific levels of capital that would be
called for in relation to specified types of business.
   Richard C. Breeden, chairman of the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission, is the chairman of a technical committee
set up to study capital requirements under the auspices of
the International Organization of Securities Commissions. E.
Gerald Corrigan, chairman of the New York Federal Reserve, is
the chairman of the Basel Committee on banking supervision,
which meets under the auspices of the Bank for International
Settlements.
   They said they expect to be ready to publish consultative
papers on their proposals around the middle of this year.